#chapter([Hierarchical Proofs], label: <chap:hierarchical>)

This chapter takes the flat baseline of @chap:methodology and asks what happens when a proof too large for one machine is cut into independent pieces and stitched back together. The answer is a family of constructions, built one decision at a time, from the leakiest to one that gives the route away on no assumption. Two findings organize them. The first is the _dualism_: decomposing a proof, unlike decomposing the problem beneath it, saves no work, so no hierarchical construction is cheaper than the flat proof it replaces. The second is the _frontier_ the family traces, on which low cost, full parallelism, and structural privacy cannot all be held at once. We build each construction soundly, read what it costs and what it leaks, and chart that frontier.

Chapter 4 built a proof that works but does not scale: the flat circuit proves an entire tour in one piece, on one machine, and grows without bound until no single prover can hold it. We do not answer by optimizing it further---@sec:permcheck showed that the permutation mechanism, the one part we may vary, moves the wall by a fraction of a percent---but by changing the shape of the proof. And we arrive at that shape rather than assume it: we take the most natural idea for scaling anything too big for one machine and follow it honestly, building it up and watching what it buys and what it breaks. The breakage is the interesting part. Decomposing a proof behaves nothing like decomposing the problem beneath it, and seeing why is the conceptual center of the thesis.

#section([From One Prover to Many], label: <sec:dualism>)

Recall where Chapter 4 left the prover. The flat circuit encodes the whole statement as one object, and that object grows with $n$: more gates, a longer witness, more memory to hold at once. By succinctness the proof stays small, but producing it does not, and it all lands on one machine. Somewhere up the size axis that machine runs out of memory, and the proof cannot be made. This is not a constant to shave. It is a wall, and the flat design walks into it.

We have met this shape of problem before, on the other side of the fence. In @sec:research-questions we saw how an optimizer handles a tour too large to attack directly: it _decomposes_ it, cutting the map into regions, solving each on its own, and stitching the partial tours together. The pieces are small, and they can be worked on independently. The obvious move is to try the same on the proof. If one circuit for the whole tour is too big, perhaps many small circuits, one per piece, will fit where the single large one did not.

Make the cut concrete. The tour is an ordered list of $n$ nodes, and we split it into $K$ contiguous segments of $M = n \/ K$ nodes each. We give each segment its own proof: instead of one circuit over all $n$ nodes, we build $K$ circuits, each over the $M$ nodes of one segment. This already answers the problem we started with. The wall was a matter of memory; a segment circuit is a fraction of the size, so even a single machine, proving the segments one after another and never holding more than one, can clear an instance that defeated the flat prover. Decomposition clears the wall on its own, before parallelism enters at all.

Parallelism enters as a bonus, and naming it a bonus is what guides how we cut. If we decompose anyway, we may as well cut into genuinely _independent_ segments---non-overlapping pieces that each carry their own nodes and need nothing from any other. Independence does nothing for memory, which the cut has already solved; what it buys is time. Independent proofs need not be made in sequence: given several machines they can be produced in parallel. The wall falls either way; independence is what lets the same work also finish sooner. So we cut for independence on purpose, and that quiet choice will matter more than it looks.

Now look at what one segment circuit can actually prove, because the cut has changed the job. The flat circuit established three things about the whole tour, the three constraint groups of @sec:proof-anatomy, and each splits the same way: a local part survives, a global part is lost. A segment can confirm that its own $M$ nodes are distinct, but not that the cycle covers all of ${0, dots, n-1}$ exactly once---a claim about every node at once, which a segment holding only $M$ of them cannot even state. The edge-cost check splits too: a segment proves its internal edges, but the joins from one segment to the next belong to no segment. And the threshold: each segment totals its own cost, but the true sum runs over all $n$ edges, the joins included. Along every constraint the cut sheared off the global half and kept only the local one. What remains is real, but it is a fragment, and the part that made the fragments _one tour_ is gone.

That loss is only half the trouble. The independence we cut for, the very property that lets the segments be proved in parallel, works against us here. Because no segment knows any other, nothing inside the $K$ proofs ties them to one another, or even to the same instance. For all the proofs attest, $K$ valid segment proofs could have come from $K$ unrelated tours. The property we wanted for speed leaves us nothing to hold the pieces together.

Decomposition thus leaves two gaps: the global half of every constraint, lost in the cut, and the link between the pieces, which independence never provided. Both call for the same answer---a layer _above_ the segments, able to see across all of them, that re-imposes the global constraints and ties the pieces into a single statement. This is the upper layer the word _hierarchical_ has promised: the segments below, and above them a recombining layer we call the _glue_. The glue is not a refinement; it is forced, and forced twice over, the moment we decompose. Whether it can be built cheaply enough to leave the savings decomposition seemed to promise is the question the rest of this section turns on.

What must the glue do? It restores the global half of each constraint, working only from what each segment can honestly hand up: the set of nodes it covered, its two endpoints, and its partial cost. For the permutation, it checks that the $K$ node-sets together contain every node of ${0, dots, n-1}$ exactly once---none claimed twice, none missing. For the edges, it supplies and verifies the $K$ joins no segment owned. For the threshold, it sums the $K$ partial costs and the $K$ join costs against $T$. Do all three, and the fragments are again a single, sub-threshold tour.

Count what that costs. Two of the three are cheap. The joins are $K$ more Merkle proofs, and the books balance exactly: the $n - K$ edges proved inside the segments plus the $K$ joins make $n$ in all, the same $n$ the flat circuit proved. Summing $2K$ costs is cheaper still. The permutation is the expensive one. To confirm the $K$ node-sets tile ${0, dots, n-1}$, the glue takes all $n$ published nodes and checks they are a permutation of $0$ through $n-1$---the very same $O(n)$ check the flat circuit ran. The glue performs a full global permutation check of its own, on top of all the work the segments did.

Add the scheme up against the flat baseline. Each segment does $O(M)$ work; with $K$ segments that sums to $O(n)$, the same order as the flat proof's single pass. Splitting an $O(n)$ cost into $K$ pieces and adding them back returns the same $n$: there was nothing to save there. On top of that conserved work, the glue lays its own $O(n)$ permutation check and its $K$ joins. So the hierarchical scheme does not do less total work than the flat proof---it does a little more, a few percent at the sizes that matter, and more at small $n$ or large $K$, where the glue's fixed costs are not yet diluted away.

This is the exact opposite of what decomposition does for the optimizer. When the solver of @sec:research-questions decomposes a tour, it _adds_ a constraint: the route must respect the partition. A constraint shrinks the space the solver searches, and a smaller space is a faster search---its entire gain, paid for in solution quality. Decomposing the proof does the mirror image: it _weakens_ a constraint. The global requirement that all $n$ nodes form one permutation relaxes into something local, since no segment sees beyond its own $M$ nodes, and a local check lets more through---nothing stops two segments from claiming the same node, so the relaxed proof is unsound. The only repair is to put the global constraint back, in the glue, at full price. The weakening bought nothing, because soundness forced us to undo it.

Underneath is a single asymmetry: finding a solution versus checking one. The solver is _finding_, facing a space of tours that grows faster than any polynomial, and decomposition prunes that space. The prover is _checking_, handed the answer and only confirming it---cheap, linear, no search anywhere. Decomposition is a search-pruning trick, and the prover has no search to prune. Turned on a proof, it finds nothing to cut and can only add the cost of stitching the pieces back. The move that speeds the optimizer cannot speed the prover, because the thing it acts on is not there.

This is the first of the chapter's findings. Call it the _dualism_: decomposition adds a constraint to a search and weakens one in a proof, helping the first and taxing the second. For our proof it means there is no algorithmic prize for decomposing, no size at which the hierarchical total slips below the flat one---a claim @sec:factorial later confirms by measurement. The total work is conserved, and a little more than conserved once the glue is paid, by a margin that shrinks toward a couple of percent as $n$ grows. _Total work is conserved_ is a refrain we return to.

So the gap does close: the glue re-establishes every global property the cut threw away. But it closes at a price that swallows the saving we imagined---a saving that was never on the table. What decomposition delivers is not less work but the same work made portable: small enough per machine to clear the wall, independent enough to run in parallel. Decomposition does not shrink the proof; it relocates it. Keeping that distinction in view holds the rest of the chapter honest.

#section([Building the Two Layers], label: <sec:two-layers>)

The previous section left us owing a layer we named but did not build: the glue, the recombiner that re-imposes the global constraints and ties the pieces to one instance. This section builds it, and the segments beneath it. We aim for the simplest thing that works, under one discipline that guides the rest of the chapter: _make it sound first, then make it private_. Each time a problem appears we fix the verification, and only once the proof is correct do we ask what it gave away. The order matters: it lets us see the privacy costs as a separate layer with their own fixes, rather than tangling them with correctness from the start. The first construction we reach leaks the partition outright. We build it anyway, make it sound, and face the leak once it stands.

We also work top down. Rather than build a segment and hope it gives the recombiner what it needs, we begin with the glue: we ask what it must check to call the pieces one tour, hand it those values as public inputs, and get it working on the assumption that they are honest. That assumption becomes the segments' job. Starting from the glue's demands tells us exactly what each segment must prove, and a step later, what it is forced to reveal.

#subsection([The Glue], label: <sub:glue>)

The glue's task is the one @sec:dualism handed it: take the $K$ segment proofs and certify that together they describe one tour, under the threshold. Grant the glue, for now, that it sees whatever it needs from the segments as honest public inputs, and discover what that is by asking what it must check. Three global claims were lost in the cut, and the glue rebuilds each.

The first is coverage: between them, the $K$ segments must visit every node exactly once. The glue needs the set of nodes each segment covered. Give it those as $K$ published lists, laid end to end into one array of length $n$, and the check is short and strong: sort the array and require it to read $0, 1, dots, n-1$. If it does, the $K$ sets hold each node exactly once---none claimed twice, none missing. Remove the check and either failure is open: two segments could both take node $3$, or a node could disappear, and what is left is not a tour. One sort does a great deal: it catches an overlap between segments and a duplicate inside one segment in the same pass, and because it pins the values to exactly $0$ through $n - 1$, it forces every node into range too. One $O(n)$ check delivers coverage, distinctness, and range together. It is also the same $O(n)$ permutation check the flat circuit ran, returned now at the top of the construction---the recombination cost the dualism promised, finally with a face.

The second claim is connection: the $K$ paths must be linked end to start into one closed cycle, not left as separate pieces. Each link is an edge from one segment's last node to the next segment's first, $K$ in all, the last closing the loop. The glue needs the endpoints, so we give it each segment's start and end. It then checks the $K$ join edges as the flat circuit checked all of its edges: each cost bound to the committed root by a Merkle proof, its leaf index pinned to the join. Remove this and the pieces need not meet; a prover could submit $K$ disconnected fragments and call them a tour.

The third is the threshold, the claim the proof exists to make. The glue needs each segment's internal cost, so we give it the $K$ partial costs; it adds them to the $K$ join costs it just verified and requires the total to be at most $T$. With every cost in hand, this is one sum and one comparison.

#[
  #set text(font: "Libertinus Sans")
  #figure(
    kind: "listing",
    supplement: "Listing",
    caption: [The glue circuit, the recombiner over $K$ segments. The segment proofs publish the arrays it reads. It checks coverage by sorting the concatenated node sets against the identity (a); verifies each of the $K$ boundary edges against the committed root by one Merkle proof, the same construction as @fig:flat-merkle (b); and sums every cost against the threshold (c). The cross-check of @sub:cross-check ties each public array to the segment that produced it. Boundary edge $i$ runs from one segment's end to the next segment's start, $ends[i] -> starts[(i+1) pmod K]$, the wrap-around closing the cycle.],
    pseudocode-list(hooks: 0.5em, booktabs: true, booktabs-stroke: 1pt)[
      + *circuit* #fn[glue]$(n, K, DEPTH)$ #h(1fr)
        + *public* $allsorted[rng(0, n-1)], med starts[rng(0, K-1)], med ends[rng(0, K-1)],$
        + #h(2.4em) $partialcosts[rng(0, K-1)], med T, med root$
        + *private* $boundarycosts[rng(0, K-1)],$
        + #h(2.4em) $siblings[rng(0, K dot DEPTH - 1)], med pathbits[rng(0, K dot DEPTH - 1)]$ #h(1fr) #lc[hint: $K$ boundary proofs]
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(a) coverage: the $K$ published node sets, concatenated, tile $0 .. n-1$]
        + $sorted arrow.l$ #fn[sort]$(allsorted)$ #h(1fr) #lc[constrained sort, as @fig:flat-sort]
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, n)$:
          + *require* $sorted[i] = i$
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(b) connection: one Merkle proof per boundary edge $ends[i] -> starts[(i+1) pmod K]$]
        + $total arrow.l 0$
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, K)$:
          - #lc[the proof must open this boundary edge's matrix cell]
          + $leafidx arrow.l 0$
          + *for* $d$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, DEPTH)$:
            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space leafidx arrow.l leafidx + 2^d$
          + *require* $leafidx = ends[i] dot n + starts[(i+1) pmod K]$
          - #lc[replay the hash up the path; the result must be the root]
          + $node arrow.l boundarycosts[i]$
          + *for* $d$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, DEPTH)$:
            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(siblings[i dot DEPTH + d], node)$
            + *else*: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(node, siblings[i dot DEPTH + d])$
          + *require* $node = root$
          + $total arrow.l total + boundarycosts[i]$
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(c) threshold]
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, K)$:
          + $total arrow.l total + partialcosts[i]$
        + *require* $total <= T$
    ]
  ) <fig:hier-glue>
]

So the glue works (@fig:hier-glue), and in working it has told us exactly what it needs from each segment: the node set, the two endpoints, and the internal cost. Hand it honest versions and it decides correctly whether the pieces form a sub-threshold tour. But that one word, honest, holds up the whole construction. Nothing yet stops a prover from feeding the glue whatever arrays make its checks pass---a tidy node set that tiles $0$ through $n - 1$, endpoints and costs chosen to match, none of it attached to a real segment. The glue only checks relations among its public inputs; it cannot know whether those inputs describe anything the prover holds. The values are promises. Backing them is the job of the segment proofs, and of one last cross-check we reach once the segments are built.

#subsection([The Segment], label: <sub:segment>)

The glue told us what it needs, so the segment is not a guess: it is whatever proves those public values honest. The glue read three things off each segment---the node set, the two endpoints, the partial cost---and took them on faith. The segment's job is to retire that faith. It must prove that the node set it published is really the set of nodes it visited, that its endpoints are really its first and last nodes, and that its partial cost is really the sum of its internal edges, which it must show are real. A segment is just the proof of those facts about one $M$-node piece of the tour. Notice what is absent: anything global. The segment never argues coverage, or distinctness across segments, or even range in the soundness sense, because the glue's one coverage sort already settled all three. The glue's appetite did the segments a favor: by demanding so strong a check at the top, it left them little to prove.

Take the node set first. The segment holds its $M$ nodes privately, in visiting order, as #inline[cycle_segment], and must convince the glue that the public list #inline[sorted_nodes] is that same set. It does exactly what the flat circuit did, and no more: it sorts its private nodes and binds the result, position by position, to the published list. It does not check that the nodes are distinct, because a duplicate would show up in #inline[sorted_nodes] and be caught upstairs, in the glue's coverage sweep. The segment proves only that what it published is what it visited; whether that is a legal share of the nodes is the glue's question. Drop this binding and the published list need not be the segment's real nodes at all, and the glue would be sorting a fiction.

The segment keeps one local check, the single piece of range the glue's coverage does not spare us. The segment is about to address the cost matrix with its nodes, forming a Merkle leaf index from each consecutive pair, and that arithmetic must be well-defined: a wildly out-of-range node could overflow the index, or land it in the tree's unused padding, where the leaves are zero and a cheap edge could be forged. So the segment range-checks its own nodes, #inline[cycle_segment[i] < n], before using them. This is not the global range the flat circuit got free from its permutation; it is a local guard on the segment's own arithmetic. The glue's coverage would reject an out-of-range node anyway, so range here is doubly ensured. The segment keeps the check not because the assembled proof needs it, but so that each segment proof is well-formed on its own, before any glue exists to catch its mistakes.

The edges are the segment's real work. A piece of $M$ nodes has $M - 1$ internal edges, and for each the segment does what the flat circuit did: it reconstructs the leaf index from the supplied path bits, checks it matches the cell for that edge so no proof for a cheaper leaf elsewhere can be smuggled in, and hashes the edge cost up to the committed root. It does not touch the edges that join it to its neighbors; those belong to no segment, and a segment cannot see where a neighbor begins, so the $K$ joins are left to the glue. As it verifies its internal edges the segment sums their costs and binds the sum to the published #inline[partial_cost]. Without that binding a prover could publish a smaller number and help the glue's total slip under the threshold; with it, the partial cost the glue trusts is the real one.

Two small bindings finish the segment. Its first and last nodes are published as #inline[start_node] and #inline[end_node], because the glue needs them to know where the joins attach, and each is pinned to the actual end of the path. Leave the pins out and a prover could name endpoints the segment does not have, and the glue would stitch its boundary edges onto nodes that are not there.

