With the chain stitched and $X$ pinned, the $K$ products are tested at a point that depends on every node the prover committed to, and the grand product finally means what @sub:grand-product promised. This is also where the bill comes due, the one @sub:grand-product named and prepaid. Plain-sort's coverage check was _exact_: the glue sorted the $n$ values and either read $0$ through $n - 1$ or did not, with the finality of an algebraic identity. The grand product is _probabilistic_, and its soundness now rests on two things the exact check never needed. The first is Schwartz--Zippel itself: a wrong multiset survives only if the challenge lands on one of the at most $n - 1$ unlucky points where the difference polynomial vanishes, probability at most $n \/ |FF|$, below $2^(-240)$ for a single challenge at the sizes we run; deriving that challenge by Fiat--Shamir keeps it negligible, as @sub:soundness-reductions makes precise. The second is that the hash is a good one, in three concrete senses. Modelled as a random oracle, its output is unpredictable, which is what lets a derived $X$ stand in for a challenge the prover could not foresee. Preimage resistance, that the hash cannot be run backward, is what stops the prover from picking a convenient $X$ and inverting it to a tour that produces it. Collision resistance, that two different inputs cannot be driven to the same output, is what stops the prover from finding a second, different tour that hashes to the same $c$, and so to the same $X$, and quietly presenting it as a valid solution to the same challenge. The exact check rested on nothing but field arithmetic; the probabilistic one rests on Schwartz--Zippel and on Poseidon2 being, in these precise senses, a good hash. We have traded a structural certainty for a computational one.

It is fair to ask, having paid all this, why we introduced the grand product back at the flat level, where @sub:grand-product admitted it bought nothing. Three reasons, and they read better here than they did there. It belonged at the flat level for exposition: it is one of a family of permutation mechanisms, and the place to meet a mechanism is beside its alternatives, built on the same instances and judged on the same terms. It belonged there for contrast: it was the only probabilistic member of that family, the only one to trade exactness for anything, and the honest place to draw that line is where the trade is still hypothetical and costs us nothing to point at. And it belonged there as a baseline: because we measured its flat cost in full, we can read the gains here as a like-for-like difference against a number we already trust, not as a fresh measurement standing alone. The gun was loaded in @sub:grand-product deliberately. Here it fires: the same probabilistic check, at the same cost in soundness, collapses a per-segment surface the exact sort would have left linear, and spreads the permutation work across the segments the sort kept serial.

#subsection([What the Fingerprint Leaks], label: <sub:product-leak>)

With the challenge in place, plain-product is sound. It is a complete hierarchical proof: coverage shrunk to one field element per segment, the permutation work and the challenge chain spread across the segments, and the challenge bound to the whole cycle across all $K + 1$ proofs. What it is not, still, is private. The products and the chain anchors we made public both give something away, and counting that is next.

So we count, as @sec:counting-cost counted plain-sort, by reading the public inputs as an adversary would. The lever shrank that surface: where plain-sort published each segment's $M$ sorted nodes, plain-product publishes one field element, $P_i$, with a pair of chain anchors. Fewer numbers leak. The question is whether fewer numbers mean less is given away, and here the section turns uncomfortable, because a smaller surface is not automatically a safer one. What matters is not how many values are public but how much of the witness they pin down, and on that measure the count comes out almost unchanged.

Take $P_i$ first, the segment's whole node set folded into a single number. It looks as though it must hide that set: one field element cannot _spell out_ $M$ nodes. But $P_i$ is not a one-way object. It is $product_v (X + v)$ at the public challenge $X$, a polynomial read off at a known point, and the partition tells the adversary exactly which points are in play, the values $0$ through $n - 1$. So the set can be recovered by search. Enumerate the size-$M$ subsets of ${0, dots, n-1}$; for each, multiply $(X + v)$ over its members; the subset whose product equals the published $P_i$ is the segment's node set. $P_i$ does not conceal the multiset so much as _certify_ it: present a guess, and it answers yes or no. The work is about $C(n, M)$ products per segment.

Knowing which nodes a segment holds is not yet knowing the order it visits them in, and the order is the other thing plain-sort hid, behind its $(M - 2)!$ interior arrangements. Plain-product hides it no better, for the same reason. The chain anchors $h_"in"$ and $h_"out"$ are public, the endpoints are public, and every step of the chain, $h <- H([h, "node"])$, runs on values now in the open. So once the first search has fixed the node set, the order falls to a second: try each of the $(M - 2)!$ interior orderings, recompute the chain forward from $h_"in"$, and keep the one that lands on $h_"out"$. The anchors, like $P_i$, turn an ambiguity into a checkable guess; $c$ and $X$ add nothing more to read. This sensitivity to order is a fact about privacy, not soundness. The chain folds the nodes in order, so a different order lands on a different $h_"out"$---which is what makes the order recoverable here. But nothing in the construction _requires_ any particular interior order: the proof asserts only that _some_ valid order exists, its edges genuine and its cost under threshold. A reordering that costs the same is another valid witness, not a forgery; the chain distinguishes it, but only an adversary reading the anchors profits. The chain pins the _challenge_, the edges pin the _cost_, and neither pins a canonical order.

Put the two oracles together and the verdict is precise. Plain-product hides the partition _computationally_, not unconditionally: it gives away the same node sets and interior order that plain-sort did, but behind a wall of search rather than in plain text. How high that wall stands is a matter of size. At the instances this thesis runs it is astronomical---a search over $C(480, 240) approx 2^475$ subsets to fix one segment's set at $n = 480$, and a further $238!$ orderings to fix its order---so in practice the partition is hidden. At the toy $n = 8$ of @sec:counting-cost the walls are nothing, $70$ subsets and a single swap, and the exact cycle falls out at once. But a wall of search stops only an adversary who must search. One who already holds a candidate partition does not search at all: it feeds the guess to $P_i$ and the anchors and has it confirmed at once, exactly as if the values were public. A confirmation oracle keeps nothing from someone who can guess. So plain-product, for all that the lever shrank its surface, is not a privacy _mechanism_ in the way the constructions ahead will be. It changed how much is published, and how hard the published values are to read; it did not change their kind. They are still the partition, derivable, guarded by nothing stronger than the cost of a search.

And the reason the leak survived the lever is the reason the rest of the chapter has its shape. Recall the two decisions @sec:stitching-tax said fix how hard the tax bites: _where_ the stitch is enforced, and _what_ the shared values are made of. The lever touched neither. It left the stitch external and the values in plaintext; it only made the plaintext shorter. The surface is the same surface, still public and still readable, which is why the leak is the same leak. But that one surface answers to two independent changes, and each oracle illustrates one. $P_i$ shows the first: it leaks because of _what_ it is made of, a bare plaintext value, and the answer in kind is to wrap it in a commitment that hides what it stands for, so the search has nothing to match against. The anchors show the second: they leak because of _where_ the stitch lives, since the verifier confirms the chain runs unbroken only by comparing one proof's $h_"out"$ against the next proof's $h_"in"$, and values compared across separate proofs must be exposed.

Neither illustration is the whole of its change, because neither change is confined to one oracle. Commit the shared values and the whole surface goes opaque at once, $P_i$ and anchors together. Move the stitch inside a circuit and the whole surface vanishes, $P_i$ and anchors together, nothing left to hide because nothing is published. The first hides _computationally_ and keeps the $K + 1$ proofs separate; the second hides _structurally_ and folds them into one. These are the two moves the rest of the chapter makes, and they are independent: the committed variants change what the values are made of while leaving the stitch external, and recursion changes where the stitch lives so completely that what the values are made of stops mattering, since none is published. The leak does not merely indict plain-product; it marks the road the rest of the chapter walks---commit, then internalize.

#subsection([Weighing the Two], label: <sub:weighing>)

Before the first move, set plain-product beside plain-sort, because the comparison settles which is better with a flat refusal to choose. Neither dominates. Plain-sort holds two advantages: its coverage check is _exact_, unconditionally sound, where plain-product's leans on Schwartz--Zippel and the random oracle; and it compiles to fewer gates, carrying no challenge chain, the $n$ extra hashes costing plain-product a few percent at every size. Plain-product answers with three. Its public surface does not grow with the segment, one field element where plain-sort published $M$. Its coverage distributes, each segment folding its own product and its own stretch of the chain, where plain-sort left the recombiner a single serial pass over all $n$ nodes. And, the inversion of @sec:witness-inversion carried up from the flat level, its straight-line arithmetic drags in none of the prover-chosen memory the sort's hint needs, so despite the higher gate count it solves its witness _faster_, by a margin that widens with $n$. On privacy the two are level: both give the partition away, one in plain text, one behind a fragile oracle. So the choice is a genuine trade, not a ranking: exact soundness and a lower gate count on one side, a compact, distributable, $M$-independent surface and a faster witness on the other. The dualism warned that decomposition has no free lunch, and the warning returns at the level of the variants. Plain-product does not beat plain-sort. It _differs_ from it, and which difference is worth having depends on what one needs.

There is one place the trade tilts hard toward plain-product, and naming it explains why we built this leaking construction at all, ahead of any fix. Recursion, the last construction of the chapter, will have an outer circuit _verify_ the inner proofs rather than hand them to a verifier. Verifying a proof inside a circuit is not free, and its cost grows with the number of public inputs the inner proof carries, since each must be absorbed and checked in-circuit. A proof whose surface is $O(M)$, like plain-sort's, grows more expensive to verify recursively as the segments grow; a proof whose surface is $O(1)$ and independent of $M$, like plain-product's, costs the same at any segment size. The compactness that bought almost nothing at the flat level, and only a convenience here, is precisely what a recursive layer cannot do without. That is why plain-product earns its place now, before any privacy fix: not as a private construction, which it is not, but as the substrate recursion is built on.

First, though, the leak, still wide open. The construction is sound and compact, and it gives the partition away. The move the leak named is to change _what_ the shared values are made of, trading their plaintext for something that hides what it stands for while still letting the glue check it. That is the committed variants, and they are next.

#section([Committing the Surface], label: <sec:committed>)

@sec:lever left a clear instruction: change _what_ the shared values are made of. Until now every value the glue needs has crossed between the proofs in the clear, a plaintext surface the verifier reads and, as @sub:product-leak showed, an adversary reads along with it. The move is to stop publishing the values and publish instead a _commitment_ to them: one blinded number that stands for a whole segment's data, gives nothing away on its own, and can still be checked. This changes one of the two decisions of @sec:stitching-tax and leaves the other alone. We change the _what_, from plaintext to commitment; we keep the _where_, the stitch staying external, exactly where the plain variants left it. One change at a time, as ever.

For the move to work, the commitment must do two things at once, and at first they look opposed. It must give nothing away: the public number must tell the verifier, and any adversary, nothing about the values it stands for, or we have closed no leak. And it must stay usable: the glue still has to check coverage, connection, and threshold on those values, and the cross-check still has to tie each segment's number to the values the glue used, or the proof stops being sound. Hiding a value is easy on its own. Keeping a hidden value checkable is the whole problem.

The difficulty is sharpest at the glue's coverage check. The point of @sec:two-layers was a glue that reads each segment's nodes and confirms they tile $0$ through $n - 1$. If those nodes now sit hidden inside a commitment, how is the glue to sort them, or fold them into a product, at all? It cannot read what it is supposed to check, and a check run on numbers it cannot see is no check. Resolving that---verifying values the verifier never sees without letting the prover lie about them---is the construction we build next.

#subsection([The Commitment], label: <sub:committing>)

Start with the commitment itself, the object that takes the plaintext's place. A commitment to a value is a single number, computed from it, that gives nothing about it away yet pins it down for later. We build one from the hash we already have. The prover draws a secret random number $r$, a _blinding_ value known to no one else, and folds it with the segment's values through Poseidon2, one after another: $r$ first, then each value hashed into the running result, until a single field element $C_i$ comes out. That $C_i$ is what the segment now publishes, in place of everything it used to lay in the clear.

Because $r$ is secret and random and Poseidon2 acts as a random oracle, $C_i$ is _hiding_: to anyone without $r$ it is a random-looking number, and the values folded inside cannot be read off, nor guessed and confirmed, nor told apart from any others. That is the first of the two jobs, and it is where the leak of @sub:product-leak closes. The products, anchors, and endpoints are no longer on the public surface to be factored or brute-forced, because the public surface no longer carries them. It carries one blinded number in their place, and a guess against that number cannot be checked without the blinding the prover kept. The confirmation oracle has nothing left to confirm against.

Hiding the values from the verifier hides them from the glue as well, and the glue is what must check them. That was the puzzle the opening ended on, and the way through is plainer than it looks. The glue does not read the values out of the commitment; nothing can. The prover simply hands the glue the same values a second time, as the glue's own _private witness_: the node lists, or the products and anchors, whichever the partition check needs. The values still live in the clear inside the proof; they have only moved off the public surface and into the witness, where the circuit and the prover see them and no one else does. The glue then sorts them, folds them into products, or sums them, exactly as before. Not one of its checks changes. What changed is only who can see what goes into them.

On its own that would prove nothing, and seeing why brings back the lesson of @sub:cross-check. The glue's values are now witness, supplied by a prover we treat as dishonest, and nothing yet says they are the same values the segment proofs were about. A prover could run honest segments and feed the glue a different, more convenient set of nodes---the made-up-arrays attack of @sub:cross-check, returned, now with the arrays hidden from view. What stops it is the commitment's second property. A commitment _binds_: it can be opened to one set of values and no other, because a second set folding to the same $C_i$ would be a Poseidon2 collision. So the glue is made to _re-fold_: it takes its witnessed values and the same blinding $r$, runs them through the identical fold, and requires the result to equal the public $C_i$ it was handed. Hand the glue values that are not the segment's, and the re-fold misses $C_i$, and no proof forms.

One join is still open, the same one @sub:cross-check had to close: re-folding ties the glue's values to _the glue's own_ commitment, but the segment proof is separate, with a commitment of its own. They are tied as always, by the verifier's cross-check, only now it compares commitments rather than plaintext. After the proofs verify, the verifier checks that each segment's published $C_i$ equals the $C_i$ the glue re-folded for that segment; equal commitments, by binding, mean equal values, so the segment and the glue worked on one and the same hidden data. None of this asked anything new of us. Binding and hiding are the two properties of the hash @sub:challenge-binding already leaned on: the collision resistance that makes the commitment bind, so soundness survives, and the random-oracle behaviour that, with a secret $r$, makes it hide, so the leak closes. The same hash, the same assumptions, turned to a second use. We changed _what_ crosses between the proofs, from a value into a commitment to a value, and left everything else standing: the segments prove what they proved, the glue checks what it checked, the cross-check ties them as before.

