#subsection([What It Hides], label: <sub:what-hides>)

With the construction settled (@fig:hier-committed), read its public surface the way @sub:product-leak read plain-product's. There is almost nothing to read. Where plain-product published, per segment, a grand product, two chain anchors, two endpoints, and a partial cost, the committed construction publishes one blinded number, $C_i$. Everything else that used to cross in the clear has folded inside it. What is left on the surface, beyond the $K$ commitments, is what was never the partition's to give away: the Merkle root, the same single value the flat proof published, and the threshold $T$, which the statement is _about_ and so is public by nature. The per-segment surface @sec:stitching-tax taught us to watch has gone from a list to a blinded scalar.

Walk the two oracles of @sub:product-leak in turn, and watch each close. The first was the grand product $P_i$, which let a verifier factor out a segment's node set in about $C(n, M)$ work. It is gone from the surface, folded into $C_i$, and a blinded $C_i$ cannot be factored: to test a guessed node set, an adversary would need the blinding $r$ it does not have. The endpoints and partial cost that named each segment's territory, handoffs, and price go the same way, under the commitment with everything else. The partition is hidden, and hidden _computationally_: to break the hiding is to defeat Poseidon2 as a random oracle, which no feasible search can do.

The second oracle closes harder still. The interior order both plain variants kept back only behind a search: fix the segment's node set, then try the $(M - 2)!$ interior orderings, checking each against whatever public value the order determines---the partial cost it must reproduce, or, in plain-product, the chain anchors it must hit. Commit, and those public values leave the surface; the partial costs and anchors fold into $C_i$ and are witnessed inside the glue. With nothing public that the order determines, there is no guess left to check, at any amount of work. The interior order is no longer hidden behind a hard search; it is hidden _outright_, as the flat proof hid it. The partition's secrecy rests on the commitment; the interior order's rests on nothing, because nothing public depends on it.

What remains is a short residual, and an honest one. The verifier still sees $K$ commitments, and counting them tells it $K$, the number of pieces the tour was cut into; that one number is genuinely disclosed. There is also a difference between the two ways of committing that the surface records: the product carries its challenge $X$ in the open, where the sort needs no challenge at all. So we have two committed constructions, the sort and the product, and a natural question between them. Do they reach the same privacy, or does the surface that set them apart as plain variants set them apart still? That, and what the segment count finally costs us against the flat proof, is next.

#subsection([Equal Privacy, by Two Roads], label: <sub:equal-privacy>)

We have two committed constructions now, built from the two mechanisms @sub:weighing weighed. _Committed-sort_ wraps each segment's node list and partial cost in a commitment; its glue re-opens the lists, sorts their concatenation for coverage, and takes each segment's endpoints from the ends of its list. _Committed-product_ wraps each segment's grand product, chain anchors, endpoints, and cost; its glue re-opens those and runs the chain and the grand-product partition. They commit different things---a list of $M$ nodes on one hand, a handful of scalars on the other---and check coverage by the two routes this chapter has kept apart throughout. Having both made the same _what_ move, do they still differ in privacy the way their plain ancestors did? They do not, and why is the finding of this section.

Recall what set plain-product apart from plain-sort in @sub:weighing: the surface. Plain-sort published a list of $M$ nodes per segment; plain-product, a single field element. We said then that the shrink bought no privacy, only size and distribution, and the committed pair is where that claim comes due. A commitment hides what it holds regardless of how much it holds: a blinded number standing for $M$ nodes gives away exactly as little as one standing for a single product, which is to say nothing. So the moment both constructions commit, the surface that separated them stops mattering. They arrive at the same hidden surface, $K$ blinded numbers above the shared root and threshold, by two roads. That proves, in the sharpest form the chapter can manage, what @sub:product-leak could only assert: the fingerprint lever was never a privacy mechanism. It was a lever on cost and distribution. Privacy comes from one decision alone, the _what_ of @sec:stitching-tax, the move from plaintext to commitment; the mechanism and the size of the surface touch cost and leave privacy untouched. Commit, and the partition is hidden, whichever mechanism did the committing.

One qualification keeps the finding exact. The two are equal in what they hide of the _partition_, the disclosure this chapter set out to close; they are not equal in every value on the surface. Committed-product still publishes its challenge $X$, as @sub:challenge-binding's construction requires, while committed-sort, needing no challenge, publishes none. And $X = H(c)$ is not quite nothing: it is a fingerprint of the whole ordered cycle, against which an adversary who had already guessed the entire route could confirm the guess. But guessing the entire route is $(n - 1)!$ work, vastly more than the partition ever cost, and $X$ offers no shortcut to the partition itself; it pins the full cycle or nothing. So $X$ is a confirmation oracle on the whole tour, the same one flat-product has always carried, sitting a level _above_ the partition rather than within it. At the partition, the level this chapter cares about, the two committed variants are equal; on the full surface, committed-sort is the quieter by exactly that one whole-cycle fingerprint. We state the finding precisely: _equal partition-privacy_.

With privacy equalized, the comparison of @sub:weighing returns clearer. There the privacy column was even only in the weak sense that both leaked; here both _hide_, and the column reads equal in earnest. What still separates committed-sort from committed-product is cost and soundness flavor, nothing more. Committed-sort keeps the exact $O(n)$ glue sort and, to open its commitments, re-folds its whole node list on top of it; committed-product keeps the probabilistic grand product, distributes it, and commits and re-folds only a handful of scalars. So committing does not carry the @sub:weighing trade forward unchanged---it _tilts_ it: where plain-product paid a few percent more in total gates for its compactness, the sort's $O(n)$ re-fold reverses the balance, making committed-product the cheaper of the two. Neither dominates outright---committed-sort still buys exact, unconditional coverage where committed-product leans on Schwartz--Zippel---but the residual choice is now sharp, cost and distribution against exact coverage, with the privacy column reading equal on both rows. What committing _itself_ cost, measured against the flat proof, is the last thing this section owes.

#subsection([The Price of Hiding], label: <sub:committing-cost>)

Committing closed the leak, but a closed leak is not a free one, and the price has a precise name. The partition is now hidden _computationally_: its secrecy rests on Poseidon2 behaving as a random oracle and on the blinding $r$ staying secret. The flat proof needed no such assumption, for a plain reason: flat never had a partition. It publishes one proof with nothing on its surface to group or hide, so its secrecy is _structural_, a matter of the partition simply not being there. Committed publishes $K$ commitments and hides their contents behind a computational wall. The two reach nearly the same place, a surface that gives no territory away, but flat reaches it by having nothing to give and committed by hiding what it has. That gap is one assumption wide, the honest distance between them: committed sits exactly one assumption below flat, and below recursion, which will hide the partition structurally too.

If that one assumption is too much to grant, there is a stronger commitment to reach for. A Pedersen commitment hides _unconditionally_, against an adversary of any power, trading Poseidon's random-oracle assumption for the hardness of a discrete logarithm, and paying in curve operations inside the circuit, with binding that becomes computational in the bargain. We note it as the available trade and keep Poseidon, which matches the rest of the stack and hides cheaply enough. Two smaller caveats ride along with whichever we choose. The hiding is only as good as the prover's randomness, since a carelessly drawn $r$ is a guessable one, so $r$ must be sampled with real entropy. And the one hash now does three jobs---Merkle node, challenge chain, and commitment fold---so a careful build separates them by domain, that a value formed for one purpose can never be read as another.

Committing also left two things exactly as it found them, both foretold by @sec:stitching-tax, because we changed only one of its two decisions. The first is small: the surface still carries $K$ commitments, so the verifier still learns $K$, which flat never discloses. The second is the larger, structural point. The stitching tax had three faces---the leak, the $O(K)$ verifier, and the external bookkeeping---and committing struck at only the first. The verifier still checks $K + 1$ proofs and reconciles $K$ commitments across them; the cross-check is still trusted code living outside the circuits. We hid what the surface revealed; we did nothing to its _size_, nor to its living _outside_ the proofs, because those two faces come from the _where_ of the stitch, the decision we deliberately left untouched. Commit, and the leak closes, while the other two faces do not so much as flinch.

What committing costs depends on which variant does it. For committed-product the fold is a handful of scalars per segment and the glue's re-folds a handful more---a near-fixed overhead the Merkle-dominated circuit dilutes to nothing as $n$ grows. For committed-sort it is heavier: the segment folds its whole node list, and the glue re-folds all $n$ to open the commitments, an $O(n)$ cost that rides at a roughly constant fraction of the circuit rather than diluting away. Either way it stays modest against the Merkle work, and Chapter 6 puts the number to it. So weigh what committing bought against what it did not. It bought the partition's secrecy at near-flat strength, while keeping every advantage decomposition gave---the per-segment parallelism and the low per-prover memory---and without paying anything like the cost of folding the proofs into one. It did not make that secrecy structural, did not hide $K$, and did not shrink the $O(K)$ verifier or retire the external bookkeeping. Every one of those three remainders traces to one source, the stitch still living _outside_ the proofs, and admits one cure, the decision we have left alone all chapter: move the stitch _inside_. That is recursion, and where the chapter ends.

#section([Moving the Stitch Inside], label: <sec:recursion>)

@sec:committed ended on a single cure. The three things it could not reach---the computational wall standing in for flat's structural one, the disclosed segment count, and the $O(K)$ verifier with its trusted code---all traced to one source: the stitch still living outside the proofs. And all admitted one remedy: move the stitch inside. That is the first of the two decisions of @sec:stitching-tax, the _where_, the one we have held still through every construction. We change it now, and changing it is the last move the chapter makes.

Moving the stitch inside means building a circuit that does what the verifier's cross-check did, but as a proof rather than a script. The construction is a single _outer_ proof. It takes the $K$ segment proofs as input, _verifies_ them inside itself, and re-runs the glue's checks---coverage, connection, threshold---on the values those verified proofs carry, all within one circuit. A proof about proofs. Where plain-sort and the committed variants ran the segments and handed their published values to a verifier to reconcile, recursion hands the segment proofs themselves to a circuit and lets it do the reconciling. The cross-check of @sub:cross-check does not move from outside the proofs to inside so much as stop being a separate thing: the outer circuit _is_ the stitch now. We build it sound first, as ever, and read its privacy and cost once it stands.

#subsection([The Outer Circuit], label: <sub:outer>)

Build the outer circuit in two moves, and the first makes recursion recursion. A circuit can be written to _verify a proof_: to take another proof, and that proof's claimed public outputs, as its inputs, and check with its own constraints that the proof is valid for those outputs. Proving such a circuit is proving that you checked a proof. So the outer circuit's first job is to hold $K$ copies of this verification gadget, one per segment, and verify all $K$ plain-product segment proofs inside itself. When the outer proof forms, it certifies that every one of the $K$ segment proofs checked out.

The second move is where the segments' published values go. A plain-product segment proof carries nine public outputs, the same ones @sub:product-leak read off its surface: the two endpoints and partial cost, the shared root, the grand product $P_i$, the two chain anchors $h_"in"$ and $h_"out"$, and the shared terminal $c$ and challenge $X$. The verification gadget takes those nine as _inputs_, so the outer circuit holds them---but as its own private _witness_, not its public inputs. The gadget checks that they are the genuine outputs of a real segment proof, and they never reach the outer proof's public surface. The values plain-product published, recursion verifies and keeps to itself.

With each segment's nine values in hand and bound to a real proof, the outer circuit re-runs the glue. Every check of @sub:glue and @sub:challenge-binding returns, unchanged in logic, reading now from witness instead of public inputs: it asserts the $K$ segments share one root, one $c$, and one $X$; it stitches the chain, fixing the first segment's $h_"in"$ to $0$, matching each segment's $h_"in"$ to the previous segment's $h_"out"$, and naming the last segment's $h_"out"$ as $c$; it binds $X = H(c)$; it multiplies the $K$ products and checks $product_i P_i = product_(j=0)^(n-1)(X + j)$ for coverage; it walks the $K$ boundary edges against the Merkle root; and it sums the partial and boundary costs against the threshold. The field values are re-cast to integers where the leaf indices and cost sum need them, each integer bound by equality to its field so the mirrors cannot drift. Same glue, same checks; only the source of the values has changed.

Why is the verification gadget load-bearing and not ceremony? Strip the $K$ verifications out and keep everything else: the outer circuit would take nine values per segment as witness and run the whole glue on them, with nothing tying those values to any real segment proof. The prover could witness whatever nine numbers per segment balance the glue---a clean grand product over $0$ through $n - 1$, anchors that chain, costs under threshold---and the outer proof would form over pure fiction. That is the made-up-arrays attack of @sub:cross-check, returned in full: a glue checking values that answer to nothing. The verification gadget forecloses it, pinning each segment's nine witnessed values to a proof that some real piece of a tour produced them, so the glue runs on real segment data and not on convenient invention.

The shared-value checks earn their place the same way. Suppose the outer circuit skipped asserting that all $K$ segments carry the same $X$. Each segment's proof still binds its own $X = H(c)$ honestly, so every challenge is honest taken alone; but honest is not shared, as @sub:challenge-binding showed. With the agreement check gone, the prover could verify $K$ genuine segments built at _different_ challenges and then test the grand product at whichever single $X$ it found convenient---the root-hunting freedom Fiat--Shamir was built to deny, reopened for every segment after the first. The outer's assertion that one $c$ and one $X$ run through every segment is what turns $K$ separately honest challenges into one shared challenge over the whole tour. Honesty comes from the inner proofs; agreement comes from the outer circuit; the construction needs both, as it did when the cross-check supplied the agreement.

And that last clause names the whole change. In every construction before this, agreement was the cross-check's job: a script outside the proofs that lined up each segment's published value against the glue's copy and its neighbour's seam. Here there is no such script, because there is no longer a public surface to reconcile. The $K + 1$ separate proofs, each with its values laid out for comparison, have become one; the verification gadget folds _this value belongs to that proof_ into the circuit, and the glue consumes the very same witness, so binding and checking happen in one place, at one time, with no equality left for anyone to run outside. The cross-check has not been moved inside the circuit. It has been absorbed: the outer circuit _is_ the stitch.

