    [plain-sort], [--- (exact coverage; external stitch adds code, not error)], [no],
    [plain-product], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS"$], [yes],
    [committed-sort], [$epsilon_"bind"$], [no],
    [committed-product], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS" + epsilon_"bind"$], [yes],
    [recursion], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS" + epsilon_"rec"$], [yes],
  ),
) <tab:soundness-terms>

So three of the family reduce end to end without ever invoking the random-oracle model: flat-sort, plain-sort, and committed-sort rest only on the proof system, Poseidon2 collision resistance, and---for the last---its binding. The product and recursive variants carry, in addition, the Fiat--Shamir argument in the random-oracle model, and recursion the soundness of recursive composition on top; these we state as reductions to cited results, not fresh proofs. And we are explicit about what we do _not_ claim: a random-oracle-free analysis of Fiat--Shamir, a machine-checked proof, or formal verification of the Noir circuits themselves. Each is a real limitation, named here and taken up again in the conclusion.

Lay the trust bases side by side and soundness is plainly not a ladder but a spread, one that runs across the privacy order rather than along it. The lightest base among the hierarchical family belongs to plain-sort: exact coverage, no commitment, a stitch of plain equality checks; lighter still, with no stitch to trust at all, is the flat proof it descends from. But plain-sort hides nothing. The most private construction, recursion, carries one of the heaviest bases instead: probabilistic coverage, because @sub:forced-inner forced a product inner upon it, and a recursive verification stacked on top. So the exactness the sort offers and the structural hiding the recursion offers sit at opposite ends of the family, and in the efficient constructions they cannot be had together: choose exact coverage and the best privacy within reach is computational; choose structural privacy and the coverage beneath it is probabilistic. One could in principle recurse on a sort inner and hold both, but @sub:forced-inner already measured what that costs, an outer that swells with the segment. Soundness, like everything in this chapter, trades. What it trades against cost, and how the whole of it nets out, is the last reading, and we turn to it now.

#subsection([Pick Two], label: <sub:pick-two>)

The last reading is cost, and with it the three come together. We have read what each construction hides and what its soundness rests on; the dualism gave us the third axis at the start, that decomposition conserves the prover's work and the only question is how dearly each variant pays to recombine. Put the three side by side and the practical question finally has an answer, though not the kind one hopes for. Ask which construction is best and the honest reply is that none is, because the three things we want from a hierarchical proof pull against one another. We want it _cheap_, costing no more than the work decomposition cannot avoid. We want it _parallel_, its work spread across machines so the wall of @sec:dualism stays cleared. And we want it _structurally private_, the partition hidden the way flat hides it, on no assumption. No construction in the chapter holds all three.

One might expect a fourth good among these---a cheap verifier, the flat proof's single $O(1)$ check kept rather than the external stitch's $O(K)$---and its absence is deliberate. Cheap verification is not independent of structural privacy: the two answer to the same decision, the _where_ of @sec:stitching-tax. An external stitch leaves the verifier checking every piece and leaves the partition on the surface to be read, forfeiting both at once; moving the stitch inside buys back the single cheap check and structural privacy together, in one move and at one price. Verification rides with privacy, then, and needs no axis of its own---the triangle names privacy, and the cheap verifier travels with it.

Each holds two and gives up the third, and which it gives up names it. Flat is cheap and structurally private, and it cannot be split at all: it is the corner that runs into the wall this chapter began at, the reason we ever decomposed. Committed is cheap and fully parallel, segments and finish alike spread thin, and its privacy is only computational, a wall of assumption thrown up around a partition still on the surface. Recursion is structurally private and parallel, and it is the most expensive construction in the chapter, its aggregation tax climbing with every segment. Three goods, three corners, one shape behind them: you may pick two. Cheap and private costs you parallelism; cheap and parallel costs you structural privacy; private and parallel costs you the aggregation tax. The pick-two triangle is the chapter's central finding, a property not of any one construction but of the space they share.

Recursion's corner is the roughest of the three, and honesty asks that we say so. Its hold on parallelism is real but partial. The segments parallelize as cleanly as any variant's, but the finish does not: the aggregation is one monolithic proof, and the very tax that makes recursion the most expensive corner falls on that un-parallel finish. So recursion does not sit at its corner as easily as committed sits at its own. It keeps parallelism in the segments and surrenders it at the end, and pays the steepest price of all for the privacy it holds. Folding, named in @sub:aggregation-tax and not built, is the one move that would smooth this corner, breaking the monolithic finish into a parallel tree. Until it is built, recursion's structural privacy carries both the highest cost in the family and a finish that stands alone.

One thing the triangle leaves out, and the omission is the point: the plain variants are nowhere on it. Plaintext hides nothing, so plain-sort and plain-product are cheap and parallel but private in no sense; committed reaches the same cost and parallelism and adds computational privacy on top, for the small fixed price @sub:committing-cost weighed. Committed _dominates_ plain on the three axes the triangle measures: there is no reason to deploy a plain variant where a committed one costs almost the same and hides far more. So the deployable frontier is three points, not five---flat, committed, and recursion. The plain constructions were never destinations. They were the rungs we climbed to reach the others, and one of them, plain-product, the substrate @sub:forced-inner showed recursion could not be built without. We built them leaking, out in the open, because that was the honest way to see, one decision at a time, what each later move bought.

So the chapter closes where its first section pointed. We asked whether a proof of a route could be cut into independent pieces and still hide the route, and whether cutting it would ever cost less than proving it whole. The dualism answered the second first, and answered it no: there is no size at which decomposition is cheaper, no crossover, only work relocated and a tax for relocating it. What remained was not a winner to crown but a space to map, and the map is the pick-two triangle. A carrier who must prove her route under budget without revealing it now chooses not the best construction but the sacrifice she can afford: the wall, if her instances are small enough to prove whole; computational privacy, if she needs them cheap and parallel; or the aggregation tax, if she needs the route hidden on no assumption and her instances proved in pieces. The contribution of this chapter is that map, and the understanding, earned one construction at a time, of why it takes the shape it does. The numbers that pin each corner to the axis it pays are the work of Chapter 6.
